<module status="bronze">
  <h>ri</h>
  <p><g>ri</g>
    <en>at, to, against</en> is a (non-leniting) <a href="?xx=prepositions/prepositions"
      >preposition</a>.</p>
  <section>
    <h>forms</h>
    <section id="indefinite">
      <h>indefinite</h>
      <p>The default form of the preposition is simply <g>ri</g> – <ul>
          <li><m>ri</m> taigh <en>at a house</en></li>
          <li><m>ri</m> aislingean <en>at dreams</en></li>
          <li><m>ri</m> Nirribhidh <en>at Norway</en></li>
          <li><m>ri</m> trì làithean <en>at three days</en></li>
        </ul></p>
    </section>
    <section id="definite">
      <h>definite</h>
      <p>When the immediately following word is a form of the definite article, the linking form
          <g>ris</g> is used – <ul>
          <li><m>ris an</m> taigh <en>at the house</en></li>
          <li><m>ris a’</m> bhaile <en>at the town</en></li>
          <li><m>ris na h-</m>aislingean <en>at the dreams</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <!--<p><ed>Add note on ‘ris a-màireach’, ‘ris a h-uile ...’, ‘ris a bheil ...’</ed></p>-->
      <p>Fused forms are sometimes found when the immediately following word is a <a
          href="?xx=nouns/possessive_determiners">possessive determiner</a> – <ul>
          <li><m>ri mo</m> thaigh <en>at my house</en> ≈ <g>rim</g> thaigh </li>
          <li><m>ri do</m> bhaile <en>at your town</en> ≈ <g>rid</g> bhaile </li>
          <li><m>ri a h-</m>eaglais <en>at her church</en> ≈ <g>ri h-</g>eaglais</li>
          <li>
            <m>ri a</m> chraoibh <en>at his tree</en> ≈ <g>ri</g> chraoibh</li>
          <li><m>ri ar n-</m>achadh <en>at our field</en> ≈ <g>rar n-</g>achadh</li>
          <li><m>ri bhur</m> leapannan <en>at your beds</en> ≈ <g>rur</g> leapannan</li>
          <li><m>ri an</m> taighean <en>at their houses</en> ≈ <g>rin</g> taighean</li>
          <li><m>ri am</m> baile <en>at their town</en> ≈ <g>rim</g> baile</li>
        </ul></p>
      <p>Note that these fused forms are rather awkward and hence are best avoided in writing
        nowadays.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="pronouns">
      <h>prepositional pronouns</h>
      <p>Conjugated prepositions are used in place of <bad>ri mi</bad>, <bad>ri thu</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>ri iad</bad> – <ul>
          <li><m>rium</m>
            <en>at me</en></li>
          <li><m>riut</m>
            <en>at you</en></li>
          <li><m>rithe</m>
            <en>at her/it</en></li>
          <li><m>ris</m>
            <en>at him/it</en></li>
          <li><m>ruinn</m>
            <en>at us</en></li>
          <li><m>ruibh</m>
            <en>at you</en></li>
          <li><m>riutha</m>
            <en>at them</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>There are also emphatic forms (cf. <bad>ri mise</bad>, <bad>ri thusa</bad>, ... , <bad>ri
          iadsan</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>riumsa</m>
            <en>at <emph>me</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>riutsa</m>
            <en>at <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>rithese</m>
            <en>at <emph>her/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>ris-san</m>
            <en>at <emph>him/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>ruinne</m>
            <en>at <emph>us</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>ruibhse</m>
            <en>at <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>riuthasan</m>
            <en>at <emph>them</emph></en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Finally, there are also reflexive forms (cf. <bad>ri mi fhìn</bad>, <bad>ri thu
        fhèin</bad>, ... , <bad>ri iad fhèin</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>rium fhìn</m>
            <en>at myself</en></li>
          <li><m>riut fhèin</m>
            <en>at yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>rithe fhèin</m>
            <en>at herself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>ris fhèin</m>
            <en>at himself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>ruinn fhìn</m>
            <en>at ourselves</en></li>
          <li><m>ruibh fhèin</m>
            <en>at yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>riutha fhèin</m>
            <en>at themselves</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

